Qiu Chenhui, China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily

This Spring Festival, an unexpected new crown pneumonia epidemic, disrupted people's longing for the year of the rat, constantly rolling epidemic broadcast affecting everyone's heart.

In the "epidemic" of the war, Lin Bingliang, a member of the Standing Committee and Secretary-general of the Infectious Disease Prevention and control branch of the Chinese Preventive Medicine Association, and Deputy Director of the Infectious Diseases Department of the National Sun Yat-sen University, not only participated in medical work, but also continued to do science popularization through the Internet. He told the China Youth Daily and the Youth Daily Online reporter that the highest number of online consultations these days was tens of thousands of people, dozens of times more than usual. "The epidemic suddenly, too many people don't know enough about the epidemic and the virus, and don't know what to do... "

As one researcher put it, many people are more worried because in a war without guns, people don't even know what the "enemy" is. So what do we really know about Covid-19, what are some of the questions that have been agreed in the scientific and medical communities, and what scientific knowledge and medical common sense can help people fight this epidemic?

To this end, the Youth Daily Youth Network reporters interviewed a number of scientists and doctors, to solve the puzzle.

How does a virus target a human

It has been said that if all the viruses are listed, the history of human development looks like a history of the struggle against infectious diseases: smallpox, H1N1, dengue, SARS coronavirus, Zaire Ebolavirus, etc. , have taken a great deal of human life. These microbes, which are between 10 and 300 nanometers in diameter, can perform an invasion in the form of a sneeze or a physical contact.

"viruses are constantly 'marching' to various hosts, whether it's a simple bacterium, a cell or a complex organism like humans, " said Chinese Academy of Sciences, a researcher at the Center for Innovation in Brain Science and intelligent technology, a virus is simply a "parasite" that can not survive or reproduce without attaching itself to other organisms.

When a virus infects a host cell, it goes through six steps: adsorption, invasion, shelling, biosynthesis, assembly, and release. The first is adsorption, where the virus "targets" the target cell by "identifying" receptor protein molecules specific to the surface of the host cell membrane. It then invades Florida, either entering the host cell in some way or directly injecting genetic material into the host cell.

Then comes desquamation, in which the virus's infectious nucleic acid "takes off" its protein shell, and then "goes on" into biosynthesis, as if on a never-ending quest for the raw material, energy and place that the host cell provides, to synthesize the nucleic acids and proteins of the virus; and then, immediately after assembly, the newly synthesized nucleic acids and proteins of the virus, are assembled into the offspring virus; and finally, the offspring virus is released, the offspring virus is released outside the host cell.

In this case, the invasion of COVID-19 followed the same path. In the first step of "adsorption" for example, the virus to identify, is the human respiratory tract and lung cells surface of the "ACE2" (ACE2) . Shi Zhengli, a researcher at the Wuhan Institute of Virology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, confirmed this in a recent paper in the journal Nature.

Until now, there has been little understanding of COVID-19, and although scientists have made some progress on some of the mechanisms, there are still many clinical manifestations that have not yet found a cause.

What's more subtle about the new virus than SARS

"CUNNING! " "UNCANNY! " Was Lin Bingliang's first impression of the COVID-19.

He told reporters that so far, the understanding of COVID-19 is still very poor, although scientists have made some progress on some mechanism, but there are still many clinical manifestations have not found the reason, if the latent period patient has the infectivity, the asymptomatic patient also has the infectivity, some patients, especially the critically ill patient continues the detoxification time to be long, and so on, is its "cunning" "UNCANNY" place.

Now that scientists have detected COVID-19 nucleic acids in faeces, the "possible presence" of faecal-oral routes has attracted attention, as has the "possible presence" of Aerosol routes. 'these are all scientific studies, ' Lin said. 'I'm sure the results will be available soon. '.

"It's good to know it. For ordinary people, washing their hands before and after going to the toilet, covering the toilet and flushing the water, and checking whether the sewers are free, will greatly reduce the chance of infection, " Lin said, through the follow-up to strengthen clinical treatment and scientific research, to deepen the understanding of the new coronavirus and virus, slowly uncover it "weird veil. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In his view, there are many reasons why this outbreak has developed so quickly and spread so quickly -- as if it were a virus

One is the spread of COVID-19 pneumonia, a new disease caused by a lack of understanding of how the disease is transmitted in its early stages. Second, COVID-19 pneumonia has latent infection and asymptomatic infection, patients with no or only mild symptoms, easy to Miss Diagnosis, how to identify this source of infection is a major challenge in epidemic prevention and control. Finally, COVID-19 pneumonia is a new disease to which people are generally immune, leading to an "all-conquering" epidemic in its early stages.

This leads to another question: In the face of the new coronavirus attack, the body's immune system can play what role?

How the body fights back against the virus

If a virus wants to invade the human body, it must break through the defense lines, and the human body will eventually discover its existence and then "fight" as if this is the immune mechanism of the human body.

"Sneezing, coughing and coughing up phlegm are all manifestations of immune cells fighting viruses, " Huang Bo, vice president of the Chinese Society of Immunology and Deputy Director of the Institute of Basic Medicine of the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences, told reporters, although the human respiratory system is an open system to the outside world, this system has many links from beginning to end, are deployed immune cells "heavily guarded" against the invasion of the virus.

When COVID-19 infects the body, it passes through the nose and mouth into the throat, further spreading to the trachea and thinner Bronchi, and then to the Alveoli, he said. However, each step of the virus into the Alveoli is met with "defense" and "surveillance" by the immune cells.

Specifically, most of the cells on the surface of the human airway contain "brush-like" long Cilia, which also contain goblet cells that secrete mucus, which surrounds viruses and is pushed upward by the CILIA, through the airway from the oral cavity discharge, this process is called "cough expectoration" . Of course, cough up sputum, also stained with a lot of virus particles.

"If the patient has a dry cough, then to some extent the virus breaks through the tracheobronchial barrier and invades the Alveoli, where the immune cells are also activated, " Huang said, immune cells are activated throughout the whole process, releasing cytokines such as interleukin-1, interleukin-6 and Tumor necrosis factors, which directly stimulate the thermoregulatory center and cause fever.

This is why humans have fevers when infected with the virus, and is a key indicator of infection.

In addition, if the virus invades the Alveoli, if causes the massive Alveoli epithelial cell death, its release death material, also can further stimulate the immune cell, causes the stronger fever response Foshan concrete performance is the persistent high fever.

"The fever reaction is actually a protective mechanism of the human body. On the one hand, excessive heat can inhibit virus replication, and on the other hand, rising temperature can enhance the defense capability of immune cells, " Huang said.

In addition to the fever, some patients with the COVID-19 infection also developed gastrointestinal symptoms such as diarrhea. This is because the throat is connected to the ESOPHAGUS, Huang said, and some of the virus may enter the digestive tract through the throat, causing symptoms by infecting intestinal epithelial cells and activating the Gut Immune response.

No matter how well functioning young people's immune systems are, unhealthy lifestyles such as irregular sleep schedules, overnight cell phone use, smoking, drinking and travel fatigue can lead to temporary disruptions in immune function that can be exploited by the virus.

Why the symptoms vary in severity

So why would an infected person have different symptoms? The answer lies in the strength and weakness of the immune system in each individual.

Huang Bo told reporters that the majority of young patients with mild symptoms, it is because their lung epithelial cells in a better state, the invasion of the natural response to the virus quickly and effectively. Their immune cells are functioning well and, even if they are infected with COVID-19, they may have no clinical symptoms or very mild symptoms.

In the elderly, however, as you age, your body starts to deteriorate, and when dealing with the virus, the lung epithelium produces interferon "half a beat slower" and in smaller amounts, which means, their immune cells are less able to release interferon and to engulf the virus, and the body as a whole is less able to fight the virus.

"If the elderly also have cardiovascular disease, diabetes and other basic diseases, the immune system is weaker, the ability to resist the virus is worse, more vulnerable to infection by the virus, " Huang said.

So far, most of the deaths from the COVID-19 infection have been in the elderly and have other underlying diseases.

It is precisely because these patients have low immunity against the virus, from the nasal cavity and throat to the trachea and Bronchi, and many other aspects of the failure to "effectively block" the virus, causing it to invade the Alveoli, Huang said, it damages the membrane of the common alveolar vessels, which carry blood to the Alveoli, leading to a lack of oxygen, which can lead to serious illness.

Of course, this does not mean that young people can rest easy.

According to Huang, no matter how well young people's immune systems function, unhealthy lifestyles such as irregular sleep patterns, overnight cell phone use, smoking and drinking, and travel fatigue can lead to temporary disturbances in immune function, to give the virus an advantage.

"The severity of a person's symptoms is also related to the amount of virus that invades the body, " Huang said. When the virus enters the body in large numbers over a short period of time, even in healthy young people, the body's immune system may not be able to control all the viruses.

At this point, the Human Immune System's "best aid" -- Drugs and vaccines -- is on the horizon.

You can't rush drug discovery?

In the face of the severe situation of COVID-19 pneumonia, "drug candidates" and "vaccine candidates" developed or screened by various institutions and enterprises have been exposed frequently and attracted much attention. So for this virus, is the vaccine more effective prevention, or drug treatment better?

"vaccines solve the problem of protecting vulnerable people and protecting groups, while drugs are only for patients, they are for individuals, " Lin told reporters. "In the long run, vaccines should be given priority, " he said, this is important for disease control or occurrence, but at this stage, the focus is on early detection, early diagnosis, early treatment, so early development or to find effective treatment drugs "very important. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
However, the development of new drugs is not easy.

"everyone hopes to have a good drug as soon as possible to deal with this sudden One Hour Photo, but we must clearly recognize that there are basic laws and time requirements for the development, production and application of drugs, " Guan Li, director of the Shanghai Institute of Medicine at the Chinese Academy of Sciences, wrote online, in response to the urgent need for a miracle drug.

Under normal circumstances, new drug research and development from scratch, to go through drug discovery, pre-clinical research and clinical trials "trilogy" before finally entering the medical market for the treatment of diseases.

Among these, the last step of "clinical research" is subdivided into four stages: Phase I clinical trial, Phase II clinical trial, Phase III clinical trial and phase IV clinical trial, i.e. post-marketing monitoring of drugs, success is rare.

"A lot of people may wonder, can we not shorten the time and standards for drug development in an emergency situation? " Guan said that it can speed up research and development, but we still have to follow the rules for new drug development. Drug Research and development is a long cycle, high investment, high risk systems engineering, every step must be wrong.

Guan Li offers a set of figures: it can take 10 years for an innovative drug to go from the lab to the market; according to incomplete statistics, the amount of money that major pharmaceutical companies around the world spend on an innovative drug, on average, more than $2 billion is spent on research and development to get to market, and from the time a potentially effective compound is developed in the lab to the time it is clinically proven to be effective and ready for use in the market, perhaps 10,000 of the active compound's seeds, before one of the compounds finally hits the market.

You can see how difficult it is.

In the absence of an outbreak, it will take "much longer than a year" for researchers to get a vaccine from the laboratory to commercial use.

The first step in isolating the vaccine strain?

As for vaccine preparation, it may take longer.

"recently, a COVID-19 strain has been isolated, which makes it possible to develop a vaccine, " Lin said. "generally speaking, it will take a long time for the vaccine to be developed and eventually used, and the sooner the better. ".

Live attenuated vaccine and inactivated vaccine are two main types of vaccines. The former, as the name suggests, is the virus after a variety of treatment, toxicity weakened, but still retain its immunogenicity, its inoculation to the human body, triggering an immune response, to prevent the role. As for the inactivated vaccine, it is necessary to carry out a culture of the virus, completely "kill" the virus while retaining the characteristics of its strain.

"That's one reason why scientists should try to get live strains in the early stages of an outbreak, " said Dr. Umagoshi of the Institute of Microbiology at the Chinese Academy of Sciences, it is also important to compare live strains isolated from different patients.

But even if scientists have a working vaccine strain, it will be a long time before it is ready for vaccination.

According to Umagoshi, in the absence of an outbreak, it would take a "much longer than a year" for researchers to get a vaccine from a laboratory ready to be commercially available.

In the current outbreak, this time may be greatly shortened, there will even be "green channel. ". Still, Umagoshi said, "it takes time, and scientists are Split Second against it, day and night. "

The ideal antiviral drug is to interfere with or block one or more aspects of the viral cycle without affecting the normal metabolism of the host cell.

Why aren't the antibiotics that beat the bacteria working

In addition to viruses, humans have an enemy: the bacterium Florida, which was once humanity's greatest enemy, like the bubonic plague, which killed off a third of Europe's population in just three years. It was not until the discovery and spread of antibiotics that the outbreak of bacterial infections was brought under control.

In the face of the COVID-19 epidemic, some people have asked: Since there is no specific medicine, why not use antibiotics? The scientists from the Institute of Microbiology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences responded that antibiotics are ineffective against viruses, and the reason lies in the difference in the structure of bacteria and viruses.

Bacteria have cell walls, their own nucleic acid copying machines, and a ribosome called a Foshan, giving them the opportunity to target antibiotics that are designed to kill bacteria with minimal side effects in humans.

Accordingly, the virus has no cell wall, no nucleases of its own, no ribosomes, and all its functions are performed by the host cell. That means it wouldn't make much sense to develop an antibiotic to kill the virus -- as it kills the host cells it latches onto.

The ideal antiviral drug, according to researchers at the Institute of Microbiology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, would be to interfere with or block certain aspects of the virus's reproductive cycle without affecting the normal metabolism of the host cell.

The Common Drug Ribavirin, for example, provides a large number of nucleotide analogs that "Replace the beams with rotten timbers" instead of normal nucleotides, rendering the virus unable to replicate and inhibiting viral expansion.

In the face of viral treatment, humans have yet to find a drug that is as universal and specific as an antibiotic, the scientists caution, so aggressive treatment often mobilizes the body's own immune system to fight the virus as if it were only biological, to really know how to fight a creature.

Because the virus mutates, secondary infection is possible, but the probability is very low. This is largely determined by the nature of the body's immune system and where the virus mutates.

COULD THERE BE A secondary infection?

As of 2400 hours on February 9,35,982 cases had been confirmed and a total of 3,281 discharged cases had been cured, according to reports from 31 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities directly under the Central Government) and Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps. As the outbreak continues, it is possible that the healers could be reexposed to the virus causing it -- COVID-19, could they have a second infection?

Because the virus mutates, a second infection is possible, but the probability is very low, Huang said. This is largely determined by the nature of the body's immune system and where the virus mutates.

Specifically, the Human Immune system is made up of the innate immune system and the adaptive immune system. When the COVID-19 infects the mucous membranes of the Airways, macrophages in the innate immune system quickly "eat" the invading virus. If the Innate Immune Defense Line is not breached by the virus, the immune response will stop here, and the virus will be defeated.

If the Innate Line of Defense is unfortunately broken, acquired immunity as a "backup" , will be activated immediately. Acquired immunity is mediated by t cells and B cells, which normally "settle" in the body's lymph nodes and spleen, and which, when activated, exhibit extremely potent "virulence" .

According to Huang, when the fight between t cells, B cells and viruses is over, less than 5 percent of effector t cells and B cells remain in the body for years, decades, or even life, these cells are called memory t cells or memory B cells.

"because of the current lack of specific antiviral drug interventions, the recovery of patients with COVID-19 pneumonia is basically dependent on the body's immune cells, called 'Florida' , especially activated t cells and B cells, " Huang said, memory t cells, memory B cells will exist in the body for a long time, always monitor the initial infection of the body again coronavirus invasion, to prevent secondary infection.

In Layman's terms, these memory t cells, or memory B cells, can recognize the virus at first sight after seeing it for the first time, even years after encountering it again, triggering a memory response. The cells'memory response is as rapid as the innate immune response, which can quickly contain the reinvading virus, Huang said.

The Human Immune system will once again prove itself to be the uncrowned King of the eradication of the evil virus.

How important is boosting your immune system

According to Huang, human history is a history of fighting diseases, including viruses, as far away as smallpox and as close as Enterovirus C, we have finally conquered these terrible viruses.

In the process, the human immune system has evolved and become more and more powerful. In the case of COVID-19, most individuals exposed to the virus had no or only mild symptoms, some had symptoms such as fever and chest tightness, which improved after a period of time; however, for those with weak or poor immune function, viral infection is a severe test.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For these people, how to improve their immune function?

Huang Bo suggested that in addition to the regular work and rest, current can eat some foods with enhanced natural immune function, such as mushrooms, wolfberry, Ganoderma lucidum powder, black fungus and so on. These foods are rich in plant polysaccharides, which stimulate the surface of natural immune cells, leaving them in a pre-stimulated state, thus enhancing the surveillance of viral invasions.

The hope is that by understanding the protective mechanisms of the body's immune system, the public will be able to reduce the fear and powerlessness of the COVID-19. "I firmly believe that the human immune system will once again prove itself to be the uncrowned King of the eradication of the evil virus, " he said
